            "answer_text": "Thanks for the A2A Let [math]f(x)=x^3+13x^2+31x-45[/math] Can you see that [math]x=1[/math] will make the function evaluate to 0? [math]f(1)=1+13+31\u201345=0[/math] [math]\\implies (x-1)[/math] is a factor. Remainder Theorem: If [math]x=a[/math] is a solution/root/zero of [math]f(x)[/math], then [math](x-a)[/math] is a factor of [math]f(x)[/math], OR, [math](x-a)[/math] divides f(x)  Now, you have two ways to do it, either do long division to reduce the polynomial into smaller order and factor, or directly factor. I know that you can do long division easily, so I will show you how to use this one piece of information to factor the polynomial completely. [math]x^3+13x^2+31x-45[/math] [math]=x^3-x^2+14x^2+31x-45[/math] [math]=(x^3-x^2)+(14x^2+45x-14x-45)[/math] [math]=x^2(x-1)+\\{x(14x+45)-1(14x+45)\\}[/math] [math]=x^2(x-1)+(14x+45)(x-1)[/math] [math]=(x-1)(x^2+14x+45)[/math] [math]=\\boxed{(x-1)(x+5)(x+9)}[/math] Let me know if you need help with this, I skipped one or two steps here and there. ",
